<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-alternate-segment-theorem" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Alternate Segment Theorem</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Circles, Chords and Tangents
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Determine the angles in the alternate segment
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    12 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To guide learners to discover that the angle between a tangent and a chord at the point of contact is always equal to the inscribed angle in the alternate segment, regardless of where the inscribed angle's vertex lies.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Have pre-drawn circles with a tangent and chord ready for learners who struggle with accurate compass work.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Help learners identify the alternate segment.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Angles in the Alternate Segment</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Draw a circle and mark a point <m>T</m> on it, at the bottom. Using a set-square or the fact that a tangent is perpendicular to the radius, draw the tangent to the circle at <m>T</m>. Label a point <m>P</m> on the tangent, to the right of <m>T</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Connect <m>T</m> to two points <m>Q</m> and <m>S</m> on the circle, with <m>Q</m> in the upper right and <m>S</m> in the upper left. The chord <m>TQ</m> divides the circle into two segments. The segment on the opposite side of <m>TQ</m> from the tangent is called the <term>alternate segment</term>. Point <m>S</m> is in the alternate segment.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Mark a point <m>S</m> anywhere in the alternate segment. Measure the angle <m>\angle PTQ</m> (between the tangent and the chord) and the angle <m>\angle TSQ</m> (the inscribed angle from <m>S</m>). Record your results in the table below.
                            </p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-ast-statement-activity">
                                <caption>
                                    The angle <m>\angle PTQ</m> between the tangent and chord <m>TQ</m> equals the inscribed angle <m>\angle TSQ</m> in the alternate segment.
                                </caption>
                                <image width="55%">
                                    <shortdescription>
                                        A circle with centre O. T is at the bottom of the circle. A horizontal tangent passes through T with a point P to its left. A chord TQ goes to the upper right. S is a point in the upper arc. The angles PTQ and TSQ are both labelled alpha and are equal.
                                    </shortdescription>
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]
                                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                            \tkzDefPoint(270:2.5){T}
                                            \tkzDefPoint(10:2.5){Q}
                                            \tkzDefPoint(150:2.5){S}
                                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,T)
                                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T](O) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                                            \tkzDrawLine[add=2 and 3](P,T)
                                            \tkzDrawSegments(T,Q T,S S,Q)
                                            \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.65, opacity=0.5](P,T,Q)
                                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.2](P,T,Q){$\angle PTQ$}
                                            \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.65](T,S,Q)
                                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.2](T,S,Q){$\angle TSQ$}
                                            \tkzDrawPoints(T,Q,S,O)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[below](T)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](S)
                                            \tkzLabelPoint[below, xshift=20pt](P){$P$}
                                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Move <m>S</m> to two other positions in the alternate segment and repeat your measurements.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Write a conjecture about the relationship between <m>\angle PTQ</m> and <m>\angle TSQ</m>.
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    Learners should find <m>\angle TSQ = \angle PTQ</m> for all three positions of <m>S</m>. The expected conjecture: the angle between a tangent and a chord equals the inscribed angle in the alternate segment.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <table>
                    <title>Tangent-chord and alternate segment angle measurements</title>
                    <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                            <cell>Position of <m>S</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\angle PTQ</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\angle TSQ</m></cell>
                            <cell>Equal?</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row><cell>1</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                        <row><cell>2</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                        <row><cell>3</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
            </paragraphs>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        10 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To formalise the Alternate Segment Theorem and present its proof using the angle in a semicircle.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Confirm that everyone found <m>\angle TSQ = \angle PTQ</m> regardless of where <m>S</m> sat in the alternate segment. Introduce the formal name: the <term>Alternate Segment Theorem</term> (also known as the <term>Tangent-Chord Angle Theorem</term>).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Walk through the proof step by step, pointing to the diagram. Emphasise that the key insight is drawing the diameter through <m>T</m> to create a right angle, then using angles in a triangle and the inscribed angle theorem.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-alternate-segment">
        <title>Alternate Segment Theorem</title>
        <statement>
            <figure xml:id="fig-ast-statement">
                <caption>
                    The angle <m>\angle PTQ</m> between the tangent and chord <m>TQ</m> equals the inscribed angle <m>\angle TSQ</m> in the alternate segment.
                </caption>
                <image width="55%">
                    <shortdescription>
                        A circle with centre O. T is at the bottom of the circle. A horizontal tangent passes through T with a point P to its left. A chord TQ goes to the upper right. S is a point in the upper arc. The angles PTQ and TSQ are both labelled alpha and are equal.
                    </shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                            \tkzDefPoint(270:2.5){T}
                            \tkzDefPoint(10:2.5){Q}
                            \tkzDefPoint(150:2.5){S}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,T)
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T](O) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                            \tkzDrawLine[add=2 and 3](P,T)
                            \tkzDrawSegments(T,Q T,S S,Q)
                            \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.65, opacity=0.5](P,T,Q)
                            \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20, size=0.65, opacity=0.5](P,T,Q)
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.95](P,T,Q){$\alpha$}
                            \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.65](T,S,Q)
                            \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20, size=0.65, opacity=0.5](T,S,Q)
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.95](T,S,Q){$\alpha$}
                            \tkzDrawPoints(T,Q,S,O)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below](T)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](S)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below, xshift=20pt](P){$P$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
            <p>
                Let <m>PT</m> be a tangent to a circle at <m>T</m>, and let <m>TQ</m> be a chord. If <m>S</m> is any point in the alternate segment (the segment on the opposite side of <m>TQ</m> from the tangent), then
                <md>
                    <mrow>\angle PTQ = \angle TSQ.</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                Draw the diameter <m>TM</m> (shown dashed below). Since <m>PT</m> is a tangent, <m>OT \perp PT</m>, so <m>\angle PTM = 90^\circ</m>.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-ast-proof">
                <caption>
                    The diameter <m>TM</m> (dashed) is used as a construction aid. The right-angle mark at <m>Q</m> shows that <m>\angle TQM = 90^\circ</m>.
                </caption>
                <image width="58%">
                    <shortdescription>
                        A circle with centre O. T is at the bottom, M at the top (diametrically opposite T). Q is upper right, S is upper left. A horizontal tangent at T has P to its left. Dashed segments TM and QM are drawn. A right-angle mark is at Q. The angles PTQ, TMQ, and TSQ are all labelled alpha.
                    </shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                            \tkzDefPoint(270:2.5){T}
                            \tkzDefPoint(10:2.5){Q}
                            \tkzDefPoint(90:2.5){M}
                            \tkzDefPoint(155:2.5){S}
                            \tkzDrawCircle(O,T)
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T](O) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                            \tkzDrawLine[add=2 and 3](P,T)
                            \tkzDrawSegments(T,Q T,S S,Q)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[dashed,gray](T,M Q,M)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](T,Q,M)
                            \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.65](P,T,Q)
                            \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20, size=0.65, opacity=0.5](P,T,Q)
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.95](P,T,Q){$\alpha$}
                            \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.65](T,M,Q)
                            \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20, size=0.65, opacity=0.5](T,M,Q)
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.95](T,M,Q){$\alpha$}
                            \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.65](T,S,Q)
                            \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20, size=0.65, opacity=0.5](T,S,Q)
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.95](T,S,Q){$\alpha$}
                            \tkzDrawPoints(T,Q,M,S,O)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below](T)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](M)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[left](S)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below, xshift=20pt](P){$P$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[right](O){$O$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
            <p>
                Let <m>\angle PTQ = \alpha</m>. Since <m>\angle PTM = 90^\circ</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\angle MTQ = 90^\circ - \alpha.</mrow>
                </md>
                Since <m>TM</m> is a diameter, the angle in a semicircle gives <m>\angle TQM = 90^\circ</m>. In triangle <m>TQM</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\angle TMQ = 180^\circ - 90^\circ - (90^\circ - \alpha) = \alpha.</mrow>
                </md>
                Now <m>M</m> and <m>S</m> are both in the alternate segment. Inscribed angles subtending the same arc <m>TQ</m> from the same side are equal, so:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\angle TSQ = \angle TMQ = \alpha = \angle PTQ</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </proof>
    </theorem>

    <insight>
        <title>Key Ideas</title>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The <term>Alternate Segment Theorem</term>: the angle between a tangent to a circle and a chord drawn from the point of contact equals the inscribed angle subtending the same chord from the alternate segment.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The <term>alternate segment</term> is the part of the circle on the <em>opposite side</em> of the chord from the tangent.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The theorem applies to both sides: the angle on the other side of the chord (between the tangent and the chord on the right, say) equals the inscribed angle in the segment on the right.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The inscribed angle in the alternate segment is the same regardless of which point in that segment you choose as the vertex.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example xml:id="ex-ast-basic">
        <statement>
            <p>
                In the figure below, <m>PT</m> is a tangent to the circle at <m>T</m> and <m>TQ</m> is a chord. We have <m>\angle PTQ = 55^\circ</m> and <m>\angle LTS = 45^\circ</m>. Find <m>\angle TSQ</m> and <m>\angle TQS</m>.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-ast-ex1">
                <caption>Tangent <m>PT</m> at <m>T</m>, chord <m>TQ</m>, and point <m>S</m> in the alternate segment.</caption>
                <image width="52%">
                    <shortdescription>A circle with tangent PT at T. Chord TQ is drawn. S is in the upper arc. Angle PTQ is labelled 55 degrees.</shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                            \tkzDefPoint(300:2.5){T}
                            \tkzDefPoint(35:2.5){Q}
                            \tkzDefPoint(170:2.5){S}
                            \tkzDrawCircle(O,T)
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T](O) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[symmetry=center T](P) \tkzGetPoint{L}
                            \tkzDrawLine[add=1 and 1](P,L)
                            \tkzDrawSegments(T,Q T,S S,Q)
                            \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.7](P,T,Q)
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.0](P,T,Q){$55^\circ$}
                            \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.65](S,T,L)
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.95](S,T,L){$45^\circ$}
                            \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.7](T,S,Q)
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.0](T,S,Q){$\alpha$}
                            \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.5](S,Q,T)
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.95](S,Q,T){$\beta$}
                            \tkzDrawPoints(T,Q,S)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below](T)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above left](S)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[right, xshift=20pt, yshift=10pt](P){$P$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[right, xshift=-20pt, yshift=-10pt](L){$L$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Be careful matching up the angles in the figure with the theorem. By the Alternate Segment Theorem, we have:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\angle TSQ \amp = \angle PTQ = 55^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow>\angle TQS \amp = \angle LTS = 45^\circ</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-ast-isosceles">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>PT</m> is a tangent to a circle at <m>T</m>. Chord <m>TQ</m> is drawn such that <m>\angle PTQ = 48^\circ</m>. A point <m>S</m> lies in the alternate segment with <m>TS = SQ</m>. Find <m>\theta = \angle TQS</m>.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-ast-ex2">
                <caption>Triangle <m>TSQ</m> is isosceles with <m>TS = SQ</m>.</caption>
                <image width="60%">
                    <shortdescription>A circle with tangent PT at T. Chord TQ is drawn. S is in the upper arc with TS equal to SQ, shown with tick marks. Angle PTQ is 48 degrees. Angle TSQ is in the alternate segment.</shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                            \tkzDefPoint(60:2.5){T}
                            \tkzDefPoint(-50:2.5){Q}
                            \tkzDefPoint(185:2.5){S}
                            \tkzDrawCircle(O,T)
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T](O) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[symmetry=center T](P) \tkzGetPoint{L}
                            \tkzDrawLine[add=0.5 and 0.5](P,L)
                            \tkzDrawSegments(T,Q T,S S,Q)
                            \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](T,S S,Q)
                            \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.7](Q,T,L)
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.0](Q,T,L){$48^\circ$}
                            \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.7](T,Q,S)
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.95](T,Q,S){$\theta$}
                            \tkzDrawPoints(T,Q,S)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](T)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](S)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above](P){$L$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above](L){$P$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <figure xml:id="fig-ast-ex2-soln">
                <caption>Triangle <m>TSQ</m> is isosceles with <m>TS = SQ</m>.</caption>
                <image width="52%">
                    <shortdescription>A circle with tangent PT at T. Chord TQ is drawn. S is in the upper arc with TS equal to SQ, shown with tick marks. Angle PTQ is 48 degrees. Angle TSQ is in the alternate segment.</shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                            \tkzDefPoint(60:2.5){T}
                            \tkzDefPoint(-50:2.5){Q}
                            \tkzDefPoint(185:2.5){S}
                            \tkzDrawCircle(O,T)
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T](O) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[symmetry=center T](P) \tkzGetPoint{L}
                            \tkzDrawLine[add=0.5 and 0.5](P,L)
                            \tkzDrawSegments(T,Q T,S S,Q)
                            \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](T,S S,Q)
                            \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.7](Q,T,L)
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.0](Q,T,L){$48^\circ$}
                            \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.7](T,Q,S)
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.95](T,Q,S){$\theta$}
                            \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.7](Q,S,T) 
                            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.05](Q,S,T){$48^\circ$}
                            \tkzDrawPoints(T,Q,S)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](T)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](S)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above](P){$L$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above](L){$P$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
            <p>
                <alert>Step 1.</alert> By the Alternate Segment Theorem:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\angle TSQ = \angle PTQ = 48^\circ.</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Step 2.</alert> Since <m>TS = SQ</m>, triangle <m>TSQ</m> is isosceles, so <m>\angle STQ = \angle TQS</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Step 3.</alert> Angles in triangle <m>TSQ</m> sum to <m>180^\circ</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\angle STQ + \angle TQS + \angle TSQ \amp= 180^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow>2\angle TQS + 48^\circ \amp= 180^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow>\angle TQS \amp= 66^\circ.</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-ast-algebra">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>PT</m> is a tangent to a circle at <m>T</m> and <m>TQ</m> is a chord. The angle <m>\angle PTQ = (2x + 10)^\circ</m> and the inscribed angle in the alternate segment is <m>\angle TSQ = (3x - 20)^\circ</m>. Find <m>x</m> and hence find the size of each angle.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-ast-example-algebra">
                    <caption>Both angles <m>\angle PTQ</m> and <m>\angle TSQ</m> are expressions in <m>x</m>; set them equal by the Alternate Segment Theorem.</caption>
                    <image width="48%">
                        <shortdescription>Circle with tangent PT at T at the bottom, chord TQ upper-right, S in the upper-left arc. Angles PTQ and TSQ are both shaded and labelled.</shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                                \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                \tkzDefPoint(270:2.5){T}
                                \tkzDefPoint(30:2.5){Q}
                                \tkzDefPoint(150:2.5){S}
                                \tkzDrawCircle(O,T)
                                \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T](O) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[symmetry=center T](P) \tkzGetPoint{L}
                                \tkzDrawLine[add=1.5 and 2](P,L)
                                \tkzDrawSegments(T,Q T,S S,Q)
                                \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.75](P,T,Q)
                                \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,size=0.75,opacity=0.5](P,T,Q)
                                \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.15](P,T,Q){$(2x + 10)^\circ$}
                                \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.65](T,S,Q)
                                \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,size=0.65,opacity=0.5](T,S,Q)
                                \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.05](T,S,Q){$(3x - 20)^\circ$}
                                \tkzDrawPoints(T,Q,S)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below](T)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above left](S)
                                \tkzLabelPoint[below,xshift=10pt](P){$P$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                By the Alternate Segment Theorem, <m>\angle PTQ = \angle TSQ</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow>2x + 10 \amp= 3x - 20</mrow>
                    <mrow>30 \amp= x.</mrow>
                </md>
                Therefore <m>\angle PTQ = \angle TSQ = 2(30) + 10 = 70^\circ</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-ast-direct">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the unknown angle in each of the following figures, using the Alternate Segment Theorem.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\angle PTQ = 38^\circ</m>. Find <m>\angle TSQ</m>, where <m>S</m> is in the alternate segment.
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-ast-ex-direct-ab">
                        <caption>Tangent <m>PT</m>, chord <m>TQ</m>, point <m>S</m> in the alternate segment.</caption>
                        <image>
                            <shortdescription>Circle with tangent PT at T at the bottom, chord TQ upper-right, S in the upper-left arc. Angles PTQ and TSQ are shaded.</shortdescription>
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                                    \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(270:2.5){T}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(30:2.5){Q}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(150:2.5){S}
                                    \tkzDrawCircle(O,T)
                                    \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T](O) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[symmetry=center T](P) \tkzGetPoint{L}
                                    \tkzDrawLine[add=1.5 and 2](P,L)
                                    \tkzDrawSegments(T,Q T,S S,Q)
                                    \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.7](P,T,Q)
                                    \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,size=0.7,opacity=0.5](P,T,Q)
                                    \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.05](P,T,Q){$38^\circ$}
                                    \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.65](S,T,L)
                                    \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.95](S,T,L){$50^\circ$}
                                    \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,size=0.65,opacity=0.5](S,T,L)
                                    \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.65](T,S,Q)
                                    \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.0](T,S,Q){$\theta$}
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(T,Q,S)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below](T)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above left](S)
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[below,xshift=10pt](P){$P$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-ast-ex-direct-b">
                        <caption>Tangent <m>PT</m>, chord <m>TQ</m>, point <m>S</m> in the alternate segment.</caption>
                        <image>
                            <shortdescription>Circle with tangent PT at T at the bottom, chord TQ upper-right, S in the upper-left arc. Angles PTQ and TSQ are shaded.</shortdescription>
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                                    \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(270:2.5){T}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(30:2.5){Q}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(150:2.5){S}
                                    \tkzDrawCircle(O,T)
                                    \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T](O) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[symmetry=center T](P) \tkzGetPoint{L}
                                    \tkzDrawLine[add=1.5 and 2](P,L)
                                    \tkzDrawSegments(T,Q T,S S,Q)
                                    \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.7](P,T,Q)
                                    \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.05](P,T,Q){$\theta$}
                                    \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.65](S,T,L)
                                    \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.95](S,T,L){$50^\circ$}
                                    \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,size=0.65,opacity=0.5](S,T,L)
                                    \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.65](T,S,Q)
                                    \tkzFillAngle[fill=red!20,size=0.65,opacity=0.5](T,S,Q)
                                    \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.0](T,S,Q){$72^\circ$}
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(T,Q,S)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below](T)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above left](S)
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[below,xshift=20pt](P){$P$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Chord <m>TQ</m> subtends an angle of <m>80^\circ</m> at the centre <m>O</m>. Find <m>\angle PTQ</m>.
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-ast-ex-direct-c">
                        <caption>Part (c): the central angle <m>\angle TOQ = 80^\circ</m>.</caption>
                        <image>
                            <shortdescription>Circle with centre O. Tangent PT at T at the bottom. Chord TQ with the central angle TOQ = 80 degrees marked. S is in the upper arc.</shortdescription>
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                                    \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(270:2.5){T}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(350:2.5){Q}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(120:2.5){S}
                                    \tkzDrawCircle(O,T)
                                    \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T](O) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                                    \tkzDefPointBy[symmetry=center T](P) \tkzGetPoint{L}
                                    \tkzDrawLine[add=1 and 1.5](P,L)
                                    \tkzDrawSegments[gray,thin](O,T O,Q)
                                    \tkzDrawSegments(T,Q T,S S,Q)
                                    \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.65](T,O,Q)
                                    \tkzFillAngle[fill=orange!20,size=0.65,opacity=0.6](T,O,Q)
                                    \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.95](T,O,Q){$80^\circ$}
                                    \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.7](P,T,Q)
                                    \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.05](P,T,Q){$\theta$}
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(T,Q,S,O)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below](T)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[above left](S)
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                                    \tkzLabelPoint[below,xshift=10pt](P){$P$}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p><m>38^\circ</m> (Alternate Segment Theorem)</p></li>
                    <li><p><m>72^\circ</m> (Alternate Segment Theorem)</p></li>
                    <li><p>Since angles at the circumference are half the central angle, <m>\angle TSQ = 80^\circ / 2 = 40^\circ</m>. By the Alternate Segment Theorem, <m>\angle PTQ = 40^\circ</m>.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-ast-minor-arc">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>PT</m> is a tangent to a circle at <m>T</m>. Chord <m>TQ</m> is drawn with <m>\angle PTQ = 52^\circ</m>. A point <m>R</m> lies on the minor arc <m>TQ</m> (the arc on the same side as the tangent). Find <m>\angle TRQ</m>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-ast-ex-minor-arc">
                    <caption>Point <m>R</m> on the minor arc <m>TQ</m>, on the same side as the tangent.</caption>
                    <image width="65%">
                        <shortdescription>Circle with tangent PT at T at the bottom. Chord TQ goes upper-right. R is on the minor arc at the lower-right, between T and Q. Angle PTQ is 52 degrees. Angle TRQ is marked with a question mark.</shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                                \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                \tkzDefPoint(270:2.5){T}
                                \tkzDefPoint(30:2.5){Q}
                                \tkzDefPoint(320:2.5){R}
                                \tkzDrawCircle(O,T)
                                \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T](O) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[symmetry=center T](P) \tkzGetPoint{L}
                                \tkzDrawLine[add=1 and 1.5](P,L)
                                \tkzDrawSegments(T,Q T,R R,Q)
                                \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.7](P,T,Q)
                                \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,size=0.7,opacity=0.5](P,T,Q)
                                \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.05](P,T,Q){$52^\circ$}
                                \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.5](Q,R,T)
                                \tkzFillAngle[fill=red!20,size=0.5,opacity=0.5](Q,R,T)
                                \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.8](Q,R,T){$?$}
                                \tkzDrawPoints(T,Q,R)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below](T)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](R)
                                \tkzLabelPoint[below, xshift=10pt](P){$P$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Let <m>S</m> be a point in the alternate (major arc) segment. By the Alternate Segment Theorem, <m>\angle TSQ = 52^\circ</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Since <m>R</m> and <m>S</m> are on opposite sides of chord <m>TQ</m>, the quadrilateral <m>TRQS</m> (reading around the circle) is cyclic, and opposite angles of a cyclic quadrilateral are supplementary:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\angle TRQ + \angle TSQ \amp= 180^\circ</mrow>
                        <mrow>\angle TRQ \amp= 180^\circ - 52^\circ = 128^\circ.</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-ast-algebra-set">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In each part, <m>PT</m> is a tangent at <m>T</m>, <m>TQ</m> is a chord, and <m>S</m> is in the alternate segment. Find <m>x</m> and hence find <m>\angle PTQ</m>.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\angle PTQ = (4x - 5)^\circ</m>,<nbsp/> <m>\angle TSQ = (2x + 25)^\circ</m>.
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-ast-ex-algebra-a">
                    <caption>Find <m>x</m></caption>
                    <image width="65%">
                        <shortdescription>Circle with tangent PT at T at the bottom, chord TQ upper-right, S in the upper-left arc. Angles PTQ and TSQ are both shaded and labelled.</shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                                \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                \tkzDefPoint(270:2.5){T}
                                \tkzDefPoint(30:2.5){Q}
                                \tkzDefPoint(150:2.5){S}
                                \tkzDrawCircle(O,T)
                                \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T](O) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[symmetry=center T](P) \tkzGetPoint{L}
                                \tkzDrawLine[add=1.5 and 2](P,L)
                                \tkzDrawSegments(T,Q T,S S,Q)
                                \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.75](P,T,Q)
                                \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,size=0.75,opacity=0.5](P,T,Q)
                                \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.15](P,T,Q){$(4x - 5)^\circ$}
                                \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.65](T,S,Q)
                                \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,size=0.65,opacity=0.5](T,S,Q)
                                \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.05](T,S,Q){$(2x + 25)^\circ$}
                                \tkzDrawPoints(T,Q,S)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below](T)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above left](S)
                                \tkzLabelPoint[below,xshift=10pt](P){$P$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\angle PTQ = (x + 15)^\circ</m>,<nbsp/> <m>\angle TSQ = (3x - 35)^\circ</m>.
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-ast-ex-algebra-2">
                    <caption>Find <m>x</m></caption>
                    <image width="48%">
                        <shortdescription>Circle with tangent PT at T at the bottom, chord TQ upper-right, S in the upper-left arc. Angles PTQ and TSQ are both shaded and labelled.</shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                                \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                \tkzDefPoint(270:2.5){T}
                                \tkzDefPoint(30:2.5){Q}
                                \tkzDefPoint(150:2.5){S}
                                \tkzDrawCircle(O,T)
                                \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T](O) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[symmetry=center T](P) \tkzGetPoint{L}
                                \tkzDrawLine[add=1.5 and 2](P,L)
                                \tkzDrawSegments(T,Q T,S S,Q)
                                \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.75](P,T,Q)
                                \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,size=0.75,opacity=0.5](P,T,Q)
                                \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.15](P,T,Q){$(x + 15)^\circ$}
                                \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.65](T,S,Q)
                                \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,size=0.65,opacity=0.5](T,S,Q)
                                \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.05](T,S,Q){$(3x - 35)^\circ$}
                                \tkzDrawPoints(T,Q,S)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below](T)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above left](S)
                                \tkzLabelPoint[below,xshift=10pt](P){$P$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li><p><m>x = 15</m>; <m>\angle PTQ = 55^\circ</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>x = 25</m>; <m>\angle PTQ = 40^\circ</m></p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-ast-proof">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>PT</m> is a tangent to a circle at <m>T</m> and <m>TQ</m> is a chord. <m>R</m> is a point on the minor arc <m>TQ</m>. If <m>\angle PTA = \alpha</m> and <m>\angle TRQ = \beta</m>, prove that <m>\alpha + \beta = 180^\circ</m>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-ast-ex-minor-arc-proof">
                    <caption>Point <m>R</m> on the minor arc <m>TQ</m>, on the same side as the tangent.</caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <shortdescription>Circle with tangent PT at T at the bottom. Chord TQ goes upper-right. R is on the minor arc at the lower-right, between T and Q. Angle PTQ is 52 degrees. Angle TRQ is marked with a question mark.</shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                                \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                \tkzDefPoint(270:2.5){T}
                                \tkzDefPoint(30:2.5){Q}
                                \tkzDefPoint(320:2.5){R}
                                \tkzDrawCircle(O,T)
                                \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T](O) \tkzGetPoint{P}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[symmetry=center T](P) \tkzGetPoint{L}
                                \tkzDrawLine[add=1.5 and 2](P,L)
                                \tkzDrawSegments(T,Q T,R R,Q)
                                \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l,size=0.7](P,T,Q)
                                \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,size=0.7,opacity=0.5](P,T,Q)
                                \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.05](P,T,Q){$\alpha$}
                                \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.5](Q,R,T)
                                \tkzFillAngle[fill=red!20,size=0.5,opacity=0.5](Q,R,T)
                                \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.8](Q,R,T){$\beta$}
                                \tkzDrawPoints(T,Q,R)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below](T)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](R)
                                \tkzLabelPoint[below, xshift=10pt](P){$P$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Let <m>\angle PTQ = \alpha</m>. Let <m>S</m> be any point on the major arc <m>TQ</m> (the alternate segment). By the Alternate Segment Theorem:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\angle TSQ = \alpha.</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Since <m>TSQR</m> is a cyclic quadrilateral (all four points lie on the circle), opposite angles are supplementary:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\angle TRQ + \angle TSQ \amp= 180^\circ</mrow>
                        <mrow>\angle TRQ \amp= 180^\circ - \alpha.</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Therefore:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\angle PTQ + \angle TRQ = \alpha + (180^\circ - \alpha) = 180^\circ</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>

